{
  "doc_id": "49312",
  "text": "Emergencies occur infrequently in primary care, and when they do can be daunting for those involved, particularly those who have a non-clinical background. Previous work has described the importance of extending Basic Life Support training to include management of emergencies using the available team and facilities. [CITATION_1] Simulating waiting room emergencies has been demonstrated to increase confidence in the clinical team in managing these challenging situations, [CITATION_2] but we are not aware of publications supporting the use of simulation in the wider primary care team including non-clinical colleagues.",
